ls, Secession and Separatist Conflicts in Postcolonial Africa draws on case studies and rigorous research to examine three waves of secessionist movements, themselves defined by international conflict and change. Using detailed case studies, the authors offer a framework to understand how secession and separation occur, how these are influenced by both preceding movements and global political trends, and how their ongoing legacies continue to shape African regional politics. Deeply engaging and thoroughly researched, this book presents a nuanced and important and important new overview of African separatist and secessionist conflicts. It addresses the structures, goals, and underlying influences of these movements within a broader global context to impart a rich understanding of why these conflicts are waged, and how they succeed or fail.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSecessionzAfricaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSecession-Africa-History-20th century. 7aHISTORY / Africa / General.2bisacsh1 aFalola, Toyin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781773851280?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781773851280423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781773851280/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles